On a purely technical level we can explain what you are seeing by looking at the [source](https://github.com/numpy/numpy/blob/9ae4f9bae9344ee0f1ca4d5767e49c196d534efc/numpy/core/getlimits.py)

The relevant snippet would be


    @set_module(&#39;numpy&#39;)
    class finfo(object):
    
    &lt;--snip--&gt;   
     
        def __new__(cls, dtype):
            try:
                dtype = numeric.dtype(dtype)
            except TypeError:
                # In case a float instance was given
                dtype = numeric.dtype(type(dtype))

The behavior you see is a consequence of `np.dtype(None)` evaluating to `dtype(&#39;float64&#39;)`, which in itself doesn&#39;t feel 100% natural to me. Others (including devs) seem to [agree](https://github.com/numpy/numpy/issues/2190). For example

&gt; Oh, well, we could probably deprecate dtype(None), which seems pretty
&gt; useless, but I don&#39;t know if it&#39;s worth the bother...

Based on this discussion and from the code above the way `None` is treated does indeed look a bit unintended, but that is just my educated guess.

