So, there is no such event, However, we can use the `Items` property to get around that.

First of all, we will need to subscribe to the `CollectionChanged` event of the `Items` property:

`((INotifyCollectionChanged)listBox.Items).CollectionChanged += Handler`

Now we have access to the `ItemCollection`:

    void Handler(object sender, NotifyCollectionChangedEventArgs e) 
    { 
       var items = (ItemCollection)sender; 
    }

As an answer to [this][1] question suggests, there is no public accessor for the parent `ItemsControl` of the `ItemCollection`. However, [this][2] piece of reference source shows us that the framework has it in the form of [this][3] field and [this][4] convenient property. Now we just have to get reference to it.
You can speed things up by [using delegates][5] (obviously you would cache them as static fields, below code is for demonstration purposes).    

    var getterMethodInfo = typeof(ItemCollection).GetProperty(&quot;ModelParent&quot;, BindingFlags.NonPublic | BindingFlags.Instance).GetGetMethod(true);
